<TEXT>
for 12 years guenter bachmann 
worked as a loading dock supervisor at a state cooperative in east 
germany then he got tired of not being able to say what he really 
thought 
last week bachmann and his wife sabina packed the family car 
with a few belongings and headed for hungary to join thousands of 
their countrymen streaming to the west over hungarys border with 
austria 
it just hit me all of a sudden the heavyset 33yearold 
bachmann said outside a refugee camp in west germanys picturesque 
bavarian countryside 
i just finally had enough of never being able to say what i 
really thought and there was no hint it was ever going to change 
the estimated 14000 east germans who fled to the west via 
hungary in the past week come from all walks of life ranging from 
laborers to tradesmen from bakers to doctors and lawyers 
their exodus occurred amid increasing pressure for democratic 
reforms across eastern europe which has rejected the need for 
economic and political reforms under way in the soviet union poland 
and hungary 
east germany enjoys the best standard of living in the east bloc 
but shortages are an aggravating fact of daily life 
dissent quickly is silenced by security forces demonstrators 
demanding democracy routinely are beaten and jailed 
public dissatisfaction in the hardline communist nation of 16 
million has mounted steadily 
according to the west german ministry for intergerman affairs 
74 percent of east germans who have come to west germany since 
august left because of a lack of freedom of expression and human 
rights 
the discontent is causing east germany to lose some of its best 
workers in the countrys biggest drain of talent since the berlin 
wall went up in 1961 
a ministry report published thursday said 55 percent of east 
german refugees who have come to west germany since august are 
between 18 and 30 years old and 86 percent have high levels of job 
training 
the survey said the majority enjoyed relatively comfortable 
lifestyles in east germany nearly all owned a television more than 
half of them color sixtyone percent owned cars according to the 
report 
but it wasnt enough to keep them in east germany 
when you read the stateowned newspapers you feel like they 
really must take you for a fool said karl dengler a chemical 
engineering student from leipzig who was interviewed after crossing 
into the west the paper declares one production success after 
another and east germanys commitment to human rights while in 
reality you still have to wait 15 years for what passes for a car 
and land in jail if you show a banner praising soviet glasnost 
hermann knorr 25 said he decided to leave out of frustration at 
not being able to change the system 
you talk and talk in small groups and nothing ever happens 
said knorr a former communist party member who was close to 
finishing a law degree in east berlin 
when i finally gave up and tried to organize illegal 
discussion groups the state security paid me a visit 
knorr said he had wanted to stay in east germany but lost all 
hope 
many young refugees said the aggravations of daily life became 
unbearable when added to severe travel restrictions to the west and 
lack of free expression 
when i applied for an apartment of my own i was told that the 
wait would be 10 years said heidi brueckl who was a medical 
assistant in gera 
i get along with my parents all right but i dont think i need 
to live with them until im 35 i want to be able to live my own 
life 
anna schroetter a 27yearold textile worker form leipzig said 
she was proud of some of the achievements of her country especially 
social programs that guaranteed free day care and other services 
but what good is day care and kindergarten when your children 
are drilled full of ideological nonsense what good are guarantees 
of a job when you have no real say in the work place she asked 
</TEXT>
