<TEXT>
nasa has white house approval to proceed with 
its muchdebated october launch of a nuclearpowered satellite to 
jupiter 
president bushs science adviser d allan bromley signed the 
authorization friday which is required before a nuclear device is 
put into space bromley had the presidents approval said white 
house spokeswoman alixe reed 
nasa administrator richard truly was informed she said the 
mission would have been scrubbed had white house approval been 
withheld 
critics worried about nuclear fallout in case of an accident will 
ask a court to stop the launch and promise to try to put their 
bodies in the way if that doesnt work 
the galileo probe will be sent on its eightyear 14 billion 
mission from the cargo bay of the space shuttle atlantis the first 
time nuclear power has been carried on a shuttle 
the three men and two women who will be on the oct 12 mission 
were in washington today for a breakfast with vice president dan 
quayle at his residence 
quayle who intends to be at the kennedy space center for the 
liftoff heads the national space council and was particularly 
interested in meeting the astronauts because shuttle commander 
donald e williams is from indiana quayles home state 
protesters claim a challengerlike accident could poison earths 
atmosphere with the most toxic substance in the universe they 
are preparing to file suit in federal court to stop the mission and 
a protest march is scheduled to begin at cape canaveral fla on 
sunday 
bruce gagnon a leader in the florida coalition for peace and 
justice said we are going to attempt to enter the launch area and 
sit on the launch pad he has written that plutonium 238 is the 
most toxic substance in the universe if ingested it concentrates 
in the bone marrow where it can cause leukemia if inhaled it 
sticks to the lungs where it can lead to cancer 
the galileo spacecraft was originally scheduled for launch in 
january 1982 but was delayed time and again 
it is outfitted with two radioisotope thermoelectric generators 
to produce the electricity for the spacecraft science instruments 
and engineering support systems of the 22 rtgs used on previous 
missions three have been involved in accidents one releasing 
17000 curies of radioactive material 75 miles high over the indian 
ocean 
the generators use the heat from the radioactive decay of 
plutonium238 dioxide to generate electricity nasa estimates the 
probability of having a launch accident that results in the release 
of plutonium into the atmosphere is one in 2800 
rtgs similar to the ones on galileo provided the power for 
voyager 2 which recently sent back spectacular views of the planet 
neptune voyager 2 launched in 1977 was the last spacecraft 
carrying a nuclear power source 
