<TEXT>
as exxon suspends its alaska oil cleanup for 
the winter amid sharp criticism from environmentalists congress is 
nearing a vote that critics say could limit how much oil companies 
would have to pay for major spills 
earlier this year environmentalists applauded approval by a 990 
vote in the senate of legislation that would impose unlimited 
liability against a shipper responsible for an oil spill and a 1 
billion oil industry cleanup fund 
but the house version of the bill which is expected to come to a 
vote this week has prompted a letterwriting campaign from a dozen 
environmental groups who say the measure would reduce not 
strengthen protection against oil spills and weaken cleanup 
requirements 
this is an industry bailout bill snapped george frampton 
president of the wilderness society 
it weakens current oil spill law and caters to the oil 
industry charged david gardiner legislative director of the 
sierra club 
the house and senate bills would have to be reconciled before 
final legislation is approved by congress 
in the weeks after the exxon valdez tanker fouled hundreds of 
miles of alaskas pristine shoreline last march members of congress 
clamored to sign onto proposals aimed at making sure industry 
prepares better for future spills and that federal law more clearly 
spells out a polluters liability 
but the legislation that has actually emerged from two house 
committees both often friendly to oil and shipping interests 
contains provisions the environmentalists say fall far short of 
those rhetorical clamors 
oil industry spokesmen have supported the house legislation and 
point out that like the senate version it would establish for 
the first time a 1 billion industry fund to deal with cleanup 
efforts the fund would come from a surcharge on each barrel of oil 
environmentalists argue this would simply pass costs on to the 
consumer and provide no incentive for companies to take precautions 
against oil spills 
the environmental groups ranging from the 58 millionmember 
national wildlife federation to the relatively small izaak walton 
league are alarmed about provisions in the house legislation that 
would 
put a cap possibly as low as 60 million on a shippers 
direct liability for a spill such a level dwarfs the already 
acknowledged 1 billion to 2 billion cleanup costs being talked 
about from the exxon spill 
override stronger oil spill liability laws in effect in 18 
states these state laws have no liability ceiling and allow civil 
suits for damages against the oil companies involved in a spill 
allow for a narrow definition in calculating the value of a 
natural resource such as wildlife fish and birds such calculations 
would let an oil company off the hook by not making them pay for 
longterm restoration of such resources conservationists charge 
the american petroleum institute the oil industry trade 
organization has argued that unlimited direct liability for a spill 
makes it difficult to obtain insurance and that the various state 
laws foster the filing of too many lawsuits the industry has sought 
a federal liability law that would preempt state laws for years but 
each time has been unsuccessful 
rep walter jones dnc chairman of the merchant marine and 
fisheries committee and one of the sponsors of the house bill 
disputes claims that the oil companies would benefit by the 
legislation jones committee approved the bill by a voice vote last 
thursday 
committee staffers point out that a shipper would still be 
directly liable for cleanup costs beyond the ceiling established by 
the bill if gross negligence can be shown and the oil industry still 
would have to pay for up to 1 billion in cleanup costs albeit 
through the special fund fueled by surcharges 
environmentalists maintain that the catch is in proving gross 
negligence on the part of a corporation as opposed to an 
individual that might work for the corporation 
a floor vote is expected on the bill by midweek and 
environmentalists are hoping amendments to be offered by reps 
george miller dcalif and gerry studds dmass will bring it 
more closely in line with the senate version 
this will show which representatives sides with big oil and 
which takes the side of environmental protection said jim maddy 
executive director of the league of conservation voters 
</TEXT>
