at least 31 of the 54 dams operated by the 
bureau of indian affairs pose a serious threat to life and property 
according to the interior departments inspector general 
the report of inspector general james r richards said the dams 
all on indians lands in the west are either in poor or 
unsatisfactory condition as a result of inadequate maintenance 
by the bia 
these unsafe dams which pose a serious threat to hundreds of 
lives and surrounding property could potentially cost hundreds of 
millions of dollars to repair richards wrote in a letter to 
interior secretary manuel lujan 
the report released publicly over the weekend has already been 
seen by lujan who has instructed assistant secretary for indian 
affairs eddie brown to take a look and take the necessary actions 
to have those dams repaired or maintained in proper order bia 
spokesman carl shaw said saturday 
assistant inspector general harold bloom wrote in the report 
these dams have safety deficiencies including serious problems 
with excessive seepage and embankment erosion that are worsening 
each year because of a lack of maintenance most could not withstand 
a major flood and as a result are imminent threats to rural 
communities downstream 
among the worst examples said bloom are the ganado round rock 
and many farms dams in arizona the pablo and lower dry fork dams in 
montana and the ponca dam in south dakota 
failure of the pablo dam the largest in the flathead indian 
irrigation project in montana could cause considerable loss of 
life potentially 400 people and excessive economic loss in the 
towns of pablo dunham and adjacent subdivisions bloom said 
his report noted that the corps of engineers in a 1988 study on 
flood control on the navajo reservation said of ganado and six 
other dams in the area it is virtually certain that these unsafe 
and often undersized dams will fail during a major storm 
