first white to publicly declare his support for the guerrillabacked 
organization he joined its legal political wing and served as the 
groups unofficial spokesman in windhoek while most of the 
leadership was in exile 
rightwing newspapers often ridiculed lubowski for belonging to 
the leftistoriented organization 
lubowski studied at two of south africas best universities 
stellenbosch and cape town and at one point was an officer in the 
south african army 
his law practice was based in windhoek but he represented many 
antiapartheid activists on trial in neighboring south africa 
lubowski helped represent 14 blacks sentenced to death for the 
mob killing of a black policeman in 1985 four days before 
lubowskis death the 14 won an appeal to have their case retried 
</TEXT>
