<TEXT>
farmstate senators said friday they hoped the 
senate would act quickly on a committee proposal that could mean 
larger disaster payments to winter wheat and cotton farmers who 
started a second crop after weather destroyed their first 
legislation approved by the senate agriculture committee thursday 
night would change the way disaster assistance payments are 
calculated 
lawmakers have complained that an agriculture department formula 
will penalize those producers and in some instances mean farmers 
could receive no disaster payments even though they earned little or 
no profit on their second crops 
the proposal is part of a broad budgetbalancing package the 
senate is expected to consider soon but some farmstate members 
hope the disaster relief measure can be acted on separately 
the problem stems from a nearly 900 million disaster relief 
package enacted last month in an effort to prevent farmers from 
reaping double benefits it required the department to reduce 
assistance payments to farmers by the value of any crop that 
replaced one ruined by bad weather 
the legislation did not spell out how to determine the 
replacement crop value the department decided to deduct 75 percent 
of the gross value of the replacement crop from the disaster payment 
a farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop 
the formula is supposed to account for production costs of the 
replacement crop in effect coming up with a net value figure 
however lawmakers contended the does not account for regional 
differences in production costs 
under the agriculture committee proposal farmers would have no 
payment reductions if their replacement crops failed to produce more 
than 40 percent of the average yield in their county those farmers 
harvesting more than that would undergo the 75 percent deduction 
only on the value of their replacement crops above the 40 percent 
yield threshold 
other provisions would require quick payment for acres not 
replanted for which farmers would have to apply before oct 1 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

