<TEXT>
after the stock markets long summer rally many 
analysts and money managers fear it is heading for an autumn fall 
the fears started to rise even before the debt problems of 
campeau corp roiled the market for highyield junk bonds in the 
past few days 
they intensified when the news about campeau raised the question 
of whether stocks might catch a chill should takeover fever die down 
but a vocal group of optimists persists in predicting new highs 
for the market above the peaks reached at the beginning of this 
month junk bond worries they say may prove nothing more than a 
convenient excuse for stocks to undergo a correction that sets 
the stage for a renewed advance 
memories of past octobers have stirred up fears in almost every 
analyst we have heard in the past several weeks said stephen leeb 
in his investment advisory letter indicator digest 
while admittedly few are predicting a crash many if not most 
feel that a correction of 10 percent or more is likely by the end of 
october yet not one of these pundits is predicting a concomitant 
rise in interest rates or big uptick in economic activity 
this is akin to predicting that a rocket ship will blast off 
without any fuel in it it just doesnt work that way 
for a significant decline in stock prices to occur leeb argues 
you must have at a minimum a sharp rise in interest rates and 
that is simply not in the cards 
many people who make the decisions at investing institutions such 
as pension funds came back from the labor day holiday in a wary 
mood seeking ways to preserve the gains they racked up over the 
first eight months of the year 
the most obvious way to do this is to raise cash in wall 
street parlance by selling some stocks and putting the proceeds in 
shortterm money market investments 
but john connolly at dean witter reynolds inc argues that the 
supposed safety in such a strategy could be illusory in a business 
where money managers are measured against their counterparts 
performance and the market indexes 
the problem with trying to duck a correction today is that 
there appears to be very decent potential left on the table he 
maintains a decent bond outlook a stable dollar and an economy 
without excesses is hardly the environment that makes stocks 
particularly dangerous 
a correction may occur given the sharp summer advance but we 
view it as essentially unplayable the fundamentals are too solid 
and the potential too high to try to sit on a lead 
wariness prevailed over enthusiasm in the past week however as 
stocks recorded their second straight loss after nine consecutive 
weeks of gains 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 3496 to 267458 
on top of a 4255point loss the week before 
the new york stock exchange composite index fell 236 to 19159 
the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market lost 374 
to 46757 and the american stock exchange market value index was 
down 446 at 37964 
big board volume averaged 16552 million shares a day against 
15531 million in the previous week 
emphatically not among the bulls on the stock market outlook is 
james grant editor of the advisory service grants interest rate 
observer who says 
stocks in general are strong yet junk bonds are markedly weak 
how to explain the divergence 
as always the correct and certain answer is unknowable 
however we happen to have a hypothesis in the form of a prejudice 
or guess the stock market is kidding itself and is riding for a 
fall 
</TEXT>
