<TEXT>
companies controlled by billionaire texas 
investor harold c simmons are cutting their stake in georgia gulf 
corp and putting on hold a plan to oust the chemical concerns 
board 
in a filing with the securities and exchange commission on friday 
the dallasbased simmons consortium headed by nl industries inc 
said it was cutting its georgia gulf holdings to 89 percent of 
common stock outstanding 
nl also said it wants to work with georgia gulf in its pursuit 
of alternative transactions 
previously nl industries said it would seek written consents 
from shareholders to oust the board after it rejected an offer to 
acquire the atlantabased company or help it recapitalize which 
would give shareholders at least 55 per share in cash 
no further meetings between nl and georgia gulf are scheduled 
the sec filing said 
georgia gulfs board announced on thursday that it had asked 
investment banking firm goldman sachs amp co to explore alternative 
transactions such as an acquisition or joint venture 
meanwhile nl industries and another simmons affilate nl 
chemicals inc have sold off 230000 georgia gulf shares over the 
last two weeks cutting their holdings from 99 to 89 percent nl 
controls 56 percent of georgia gulfs outstanding common stock 
whicle nl chemicals has 33 percent 
the shares were sold in blocks ranging from 6300 shares to 
33500 shares for prices between 5850 and 5950 per share 
the two simmons companies said they will continue selling shares 
if they stay above the 55 price they believe could be obtained 
through leveraged recapitalization merger or other transaction 
but nl and nlc also said they would resume their dumptheboard 
plan in georgia gulf takes steps not reasonably calculated to 
realize at least 55 per share for stockholders 
</TEXT>
